00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:38.390
So can you tell us a bit about
the thinking behind the repertoire

00:03:38.390 --> 00:03:40.680
selection for this program?

00:03:40.680 --> 00:03:44.100
So we have the Haydn and the
Brahms and the vaporing [sp].

00:03:44.100 --> 00:03:49.260
&gt;&gt; Peter Stumpf: Well, the Bones
piano quartet is, you know,

00:03:49.260 --> 00:03:52.790
one of his greatest
chamber music works.

00:03:52.790 --> 00:03:56.140
I think it's very and it's
a very sophisticated piece

00:03:56.140 --> 00:04:03.040
and it's a very, it's a big piece.

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:05.430
It's very, substantial.

00:04:05.430 --> 00:04:10.990
And one of his longer
works actually.

00:04:10.990 --> 00:04:17.970 position:56%
So the idea is to keep the beginning
of the program, the first half

00:04:17.970 --> 00:04:21.970
of the program on the shorter side

00:04:21.970 --> 00:04:26.170
and also somewhat on
the lighter side.

00:04:26.170 --> 00:04:34.750 position:56%
And so for that reason the Haydn was
selected, the Haydn String Quartet,

00:04:34.750 --> 00:04:37.570
which I think is a very
nice balance for the bonds.

00:04:37.570 --> 00:04:43.380
And then the vaporing that we're
doing, the idea with that was

00:04:43.380 --> 00:04:45.590
in part that it's brevity.

00:04:45.590 --> 00:04:50.560
It's not as short as most
vaporing pieces are, but it is,

00:04:50.560 --> 00:04:54.700
you know, a very compact work.

00:04:54.700 --> 00:05:01.160
And also it's very rarely played
and very few people know it.

00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:06.840
So that was sort of -- those
two elements were the two things

00:05:06.840 --> 00:05:11.550
that were the basic idea
behind doing the vaporing.

00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:16.370
I think in addition to that
though because the Brahms is

00:05:16.370 --> 00:05:20.830
such a great piece it's important
to make sure that the pieces

00:05:20.830 --> 00:05:28.430
that precede it are in that
realm and level of composition,

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:32.070
which I think both of these
without question are, you know,

00:05:32.070 --> 00:05:34.900
said that was also
one of the reasons

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:38.610
for choosing the Haydn
and the vaporing.

00:05:38.610 --> 00:05:39.910
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Great.

