solo Concerto with orchestra

00:07:08.800 --> 00:07:13.580
or in an orchestra or
in a string quartet.

00:07:13.580 --> 00:07:16.450
Obviously the way you approach
it is slightly different,

00:07:16.450 --> 00:07:19.220
but I think if you come
at it with an open mind

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:24.520
and in a collaborative
spirit, then I don't know,

00:07:24.520 --> 00:07:25.860
these things are all
kind of similar.

00:07:25.860 --> 00:07:29.040
We don't have any issues
working together for instance,.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:30.340
[laughs]

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:31.640
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Great, cool.

00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:33.780
What kind of -- sorry, I'm going to
get silly with questions for a bit,

00:07:33.780 --> 00:07:39.060
but what might be some issues
where you have very strong feelings

00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:41.690
about that say the group
is on one side and one

00:07:41.690 --> 00:07:43.320
of you is on a different position.

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:45.250
Would that be something
having to do with tempo,

00:07:45.250 --> 00:07:48.670
performance practice
issues, articulation even.

00:07:48.670 --> 00:07:51.130
Or do you kind of just
it's like a relationship.

00:07:51.130 --> 00:07:52.820
You kind of give and
take and find a balance

00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:56.980
and somehow have a nice
combo platter at the end.

00:07:56.980 --> 00:07:59.230
&gt;&gt; Robin Scott: What you said
at the end is about right.

00:07:59.230 --> 00:08:04.230
I think oftentimes also what
people perceive at the time

00:08:04.230 --> 00:08:08.910
to be contradicting
ideas, oftentimes aren't.

00:08:08.910 --> 00:08:13.390
There are many times in music
I think when you can try

00:08:13.390 --> 00:08:18.440
to actually combine two things
that almost seem to be opposites.

00:08:18.440 --> 00:08:21.760
But when you put them together
actually make something that's far

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:24.430
stronger than just one of
those things by itself.

00:08:24.430 --> 00:08:27.200
I mean I often think that about
when you have people who think

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:31.510
about a piece very
differently, they're looking --

00:08:31.510 --> 00:08:33.410
they're coming from a
different direction.

00:08:33.410 --> 00:08:36.230
They're looking for a little bit
different things perhaps in it,

00:08:36.230 --> 00:08:40.000
but when you get both of
those qualities actually,

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.810
you get a better product
than maybe what you thought,

00:08:44.810 --> 00:08:47.350
how you thought you loved
it in the first place

00:08:47.350 --> 00:08:51.250
when you take other
people's ideas into account.

00:08:51.250 --> 00:08:53.700 position:56%
And then you also are forced to find

00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:57.200
out what you really
like about the piece.

00:08:57.200 --> 00:09:01.420
Was it really the speed at which
it goes by that you like it.

00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:02.870
Well, no, that's probably
not what it is.

00:09:02.870 --> 00:09:08.200
It's other deeper things and then
you find you can actually do your

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:13.090
own ideas and add to them
other people's suggestions

00:09:13.090 --> 00:09:20.080
and the product oftentimes is
much better than it was initially.

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:21.380
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Great.

00:09:21.380 --> 00:09:23.100
So since we're in a library,
we're going to go a little nerdy

