00:30:28.910 --> 00:30:32.010
there's actually great
restaurants there

00:30:32.010 --> 00:30:34.860
and art galleries and all kinds.

00:30:34.860 --> 00:30:40.730
It's artistic oriented community.

00:30:40.730 --> 00:30:46.130
Marlboro itself has a
post office and an inn.

00:30:46.130 --> 00:30:50.600
There is an actual inn right
there in the center, and a church,

00:30:50.600 --> 00:30:55.100 position:56%
so there's inn, church, post office.

00:30:55.100 --> 00:30:56.400
And --

00:30:56.400 --> 00:30:57.700
&gt;&gt; College.

00:30:57.700 --> 00:30:59.250
&gt;&gt; Peter Stumpf: And then
the college, but that's not

00:30:59.250 --> 00:31:00.760
in the center of the town.

00:31:00.760 --> 00:31:05.150
The college you have to drive
to the college from there.

00:31:05.150 --> 00:31:06.450
&gt;&gt; Alexi Kenney: It's really
in the middle of the woods.

00:31:06.450 --> 00:31:09.470
&gt;&gt; Peter Stumpf: It's in the middle
of the woods up in the mountains.

00:31:09.470 --> 00:31:13.970
So it's, yeah, it's
beautiful, quiet country there.

00:31:13.970 --> 00:31:16.250
Bears and mooses.

00:31:16.250 --> 00:31:17.550
[laughs] But, yeah.

00:31:17.550 --> 00:31:22.690
So actually there, there
is only this one small inn

00:31:22.690 --> 00:31:26.030
and then there are a
couple other inns nearby.

00:31:26.030 --> 00:31:31.470
And there are people, a lot of
people that come up just to be

00:31:31.470 --> 00:31:33.550
in Vermont and to go
to the concerts.

00:31:33.550 --> 00:31:39.440
And some stay for the
whole summer to do that.

00:31:39.440 --> 00:31:42.820
And some people just
come up for a weekend.

00:31:42.820 --> 00:31:45.200
It's a great weekend trip.

00:31:45.200 --> 00:31:51.060
You know, because then you can --

00:31:51.060 --> 00:31:52.710
the Sunday concerts
in the afternoon,

00:31:52.710 --> 00:31:56.190
so you can travel somewhere in
that evening if you need to.

00:31:56.190 --> 00:31:58.070
And the Saturday concerts at night.

00:31:58.070 --> 00:32:01.050
So it's really set up for people
to come up for the weekend,

00:32:01.050 --> 00:32:03.580
and I think a lot of people
from New York do that, you know,

00:32:03.580 --> 00:32:05.930
because they can just
go up for a weekend

00:32:05.930 --> 00:32:10.560
and hear a couple of concerts.

00:32:10.560 --> 00:32:14.550
So, you know, whenever
you have the time

00:32:14.550 --> 00:32:18.500
and interest for I think really.

00:32:18.500 --> 00:32:20.780
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Anyone
else any suggestions,

00:32:20.780 --> 00:32:23.890
places to steer clear of.

00:32:23.890 --> 00:32:26.360
[laughs] Okay.

00:32:26.360 --> 00:32:28.320
So last question I'll throw out

00:32:28.320 --> 00:32:33.670
and then we'll let you guys have
a little dinner break is perhaps a

00:32:33.670 --> 00:32:34.970
controversial question,
but you don't have

00:32:34.970 --> 00:32:36.980
to get political or anything.

00:32:36.980 --> 00:32:41.460
How do you interpret your roles
in society as artists in terms

00:32:41.460 --> 00:32:47.550 position:56%
of what do you think your role is in
inspiring people to think critically

00:32:47.550 --> 00:32:51.100
about their lives, about music

00:32:51.100 --> 00:32:54.480
or about the way music
can affect positive change

00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:56.190
or anything in that world?

00:32:56.190 --> 00:32:59.280
If you have any thoughts
that don't cause you

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:03.990
to reveal anything too sensitive,
feel free to jump in there.

00:33:03.990 --> 00:33:06.260
I think the reason for my
question is I think we're

00:33:06.260 --> 00:33:07.560
in Washington, right.

00:33:07.560 --> 00:33:09.850
So Washington is an
epicenter of a lot

00:33:09.850 --> 00:33:11.510
of different things
going on in society.

00:33:11.510 --> 00:33:15.260
For better and for
worse, and the Library

00:33:15.260 --> 00:33:17.480
of Congress definitely
values the role of the arts

00:33:17.480 --> 00:33:19.400
and culture in humanities.

00:33:19.400 --> 00:33:24.950 position:56%
And we really want to know where you
all are at and how we can complement

00:33:24.950 --> 00:33:28.590
that work to really make sure
that we're serving the population.

00:33:28.590 --> 00:33:33.250
I guess. Like education, work.

00:33:33.250 --> 00:33:35.580
Do you do performances
for specific causes?

00:33:35.580 --> 00:33:38.750
Do you steer clear of it all
and just focus on the music

00:33:38.750 --> 00:33:40.970 position:56%
and that's the way you deal with it.

00:33:40.970 --> 00:33:42.510
&gt;&gt; Peter Stumpf: I think each one

00:33:42.510 --> 00:33:46.980
of us does something
different, you know.

00:33:46.980 --> 00:33:51.350
I mean we all have different
ways that can do that.

00:33:51.350 --> 00:33:56.730
I mean at this point in my life
I'm a professor at the University.

00:33:56.730 --> 00:34:02.300
So I mean what I'm doing
is, you know, mentoring

00:34:02.300 --> 00:34:11.700
and helping young aspiring
musicians to participate in music,

00:34:11.700 --> 00:34:17.650
and to get involved, and
to see it go forward.

00:34:17.650 --> 00:34:24.960
And I think, you know, I
think probably most people

00:34:24.960 --> 00:34:30.370 position:56%
that are involved in the arts in
general it comes from a certain kind

00:34:30.370 --> 00:34:39.260
of it's about inspiration that
comes from whatever the art

00:34:39.260 --> 00:34:45.850
that that particular person is
drawn in by, whether it be visual

00:34:45.850 --> 00:34:49.250
or musical or writing, whatever.

00:34:49.250 --> 00:34:59.560
And so I think ultimately it's
in particular for what we do,

00:34:59.560 --> 00:35:05.080
we're bringing something to life
that otherwise would not, you know,

00:35:05.080 --> 00:35:08.990 position:56%
there's no way to know what you --
there are a few people that can look

00:35:08.990 --> 00:35:12.710
at a score and know exactly what
it sounds like and experience it

00:35:12.710 --> 00:35:16.020
without ever having heard it.

00:35:16.020 --> 00:35:18.190
[laughs] You actually can.

00:35:18.190 --> 00:35:19.930
Some people can.

00:35:19.930 --> 00:35:25.500
But generally it has to be played.

00:35:25.500 --> 00:35:34.920
And there's such a huge range
of different areas of music

00:35:34.920 --> 00:35:36.920
that people get involved in.

00:35:36.920 --> 00:35:40.130
You know, it's just it's
endless and limitless.

00:35:40.130 --> 00:35:46.190
But I think it's about the
inspiration and the connection

00:35:46.190 --> 00:35:57.030
between what it affirms for
us in our experiences in life

00:35:57.030 --> 00:36:00.150
that we don't speak about.

00:36:00.150 --> 00:36:03.330
Things we don't say.

00:36:03.330 --> 00:36:10.540
Things we don't talk about, but
the things that we know to be true,

00:36:10.540 --> 00:36:13.640
but often only internally.

00:36:13.640 --> 00:36:19.980 position:56%
So we don't realize necessarily
this is something that we all share.

00:36:19.980 --> 00:36:27.210
You know, and when each piece
of music has within it some --

00:36:27.210 --> 00:36:34.560
well I'll say a great range
of expressive qualities

00:36:34.560 --> 00:36:42.920
that go past our intellectual
experience and understanding

00:36:42.920 --> 00:36:52.850
and touch the inner kind of core
of each person in different ways.

00:36:52.850 --> 00:36:55.820
But it affirms for
them the existence

00:36:55.820 --> 00:37:00.540
of this reality that they have.

00:37:00.540 --> 00:37:05.010
And there's something
tremendously comforting about that.

00:37:05.010 --> 00:37:11.910
And also gives you a sense
of community, you know,

00:37:11.910 --> 00:37:15.420
and a sense that you're
not alone with that feeling

00:37:15.420 --> 00:37:18.770
or that experience in your life.

00:37:18.770 --> 00:37:20.070
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Thank you.

00:37:20.070 --> 00:37:21.370
That's very insightful.

00:37:21.370 --> 00:37:22.670
I appreciate it.

00:37:22.670 --> 00:37:23.970
Anyone else have some thoughts?

00:37:23.970 --> 00:37:25.270
You can say no.

00:37:25.270 --> 00:37:26.570
That's okay.

00:37:26.570 --> 00:37:27.870
&gt;&gt; Alexi Kenney: I was going
to say I mean just in terms

00:37:27.870 --> 00:37:32.480 position:56%
of my experience, I do a lot of
traveling to perform with orchestras

00:37:32.480 --> 00:37:34.600
or recitals around the country.

00:37:34.600 --> 00:37:37.860
And a lot of the time kind of
in the middle of the country

00:37:37.860 --> 00:37:41.080
where I wouldn't necessarily
go on vacation

00:37:41.080 --> 00:37:44.400
or travel too, particularly.

00:37:44.400 --> 00:37:47.080
And I'm often asked to do some sort

00:37:47.080 --> 00:37:49.820
of educational outreach
when I travel.

00:37:49.820 --> 00:37:55.190
And this is something that
I've grown to really love.

00:37:55.190 --> 00:38:00.330
Sometimes even more than
playing the concert itself.

00:38:00.330 --> 00:38:03.400
Although, of course, I love
performing and all of that,

00:38:03.400 --> 00:38:08.920
but there's something
incredibly important obviously

00:38:08.920 --> 00:38:10.850
about playing for kids.

00:38:10.850 --> 00:38:18.630
And I think a lot of that -- when
I play for a school, for instance,,

00:38:18.630 --> 00:38:24.540
I find myself being as
passionate or even feel

00:38:24.540 --> 00:38:32.520
like being more passionate is
so important, because, you know,

00:38:32.520 --> 00:38:36.420
to go along with inspiration
and all of this, of course,

00:38:36.420 --> 00:38:40.850
I agree that yes there's
this incredible quality

00:38:40.850 --> 00:38:43.790
about music that is unspeakable..

00:38:43.790 --> 00:38:47.520
You can't put it into words.

00:38:47.520 --> 00:38:51.920
And that beauty for me keeps me
going as a musician day to day.

00:38:51.920 --> 00:38:56.380
But for a group of kids who
are listening to music maybe

00:38:56.380 --> 00:38:58.990
for the first time
listening to a violin player,

00:38:58.990 --> 00:39:05.890
I think what touches somebody
is energy and raw kind

00:39:05.890 --> 00:39:08.900
of that sort of inspiration.

00:39:08.900 --> 00:39:11.320
Somebody is seeing somebody
very, very passionate

00:39:11.320 --> 00:39:14.320
about something they love to do.

00:39:14.320 --> 00:39:21.850
And I feel that's a great duty
for my life to bring to people,

00:39:21.850 --> 00:39:26.070
especially to kids but also in
every performance, you know,

00:39:26.070 --> 00:39:31.680
just giving it 120 percent
because why do it otherwise.

00:39:31.680 --> 00:39:32.980
&gt;&gt; Robin Scott: Yeah.

00:39:32.980 --> 00:39:36.630
You have you have the chance to
possibly really reach someone

00:39:36.630 --> 00:39:43.240
who may never heard a violin or
any classical music, for instance,,

00:39:43.240 --> 00:39:49.230 position:56%
and then you really I think it helps
you find what you really want to say

00:39:49.230 --> 00:39:52.840
in a way, because they don't
care about all the other details

00:39:52.840 --> 00:39:58.880
that other professionals who might
listen to you, might care about.

00:39:58.880 --> 00:40:01.430
And they also can tell --

00:40:01.430 --> 00:40:05.820
I think they can see right
through fakery [laughs]

00:40:05.820 --> 00:40:09.240
or disingenuous sorts of things.

00:40:09.240 --> 00:40:16.870
And so you have to be really
honest and do your very best

00:40:16.870 --> 00:40:19.000
to really command their attention.

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:20.740
That's difficult.

00:40:20.740 --> 00:40:26.620
[laughs] But it's totally worth it.

00:40:26.620 --> 00:40:27.920
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Great.

00:40:27.920 --> 00:40:29.300
Zoltan, did you want
to add anything?

00:40:29.300 --> 00:40:32.810
&gt;&gt; Zoltan Fejervan: I can
only agree with everybody.

00:40:32.810 --> 00:40:38.210
It just comes to my mind what
Gabriel Garcia Marquez wrote

00:40:38.210 --> 00:40:41.390
about him being a writer.

00:40:41.390 --> 00:40:46.420 position:56%
And I think he writes that you
shouldn't be a writer if you realize

00:40:46.420 --> 00:40:49.700 position:56%
that you can't live without writing.

00:40:49.700 --> 00:40:53.780
So it's something similar
with the musician I think.

00:40:53.780 --> 00:40:59.850
So we have to realize if you
can't live without making music,

00:40:59.850 --> 00:41:04.140
that's like so if we can live

00:41:04.140 --> 00:41:09.300
without making music then
let's stop making music.

00:41:09.300 --> 00:41:17.450
And we certainly have to have a
very strong message in our playing.

00:41:17.450 --> 00:41:21.270
That's what matters for sure.

00:41:21.270 --> 00:41:23.030
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Thank you
for sharing those thoughts.

00:41:23.030 --> 00:41:27.760
I think it means a lot for all of
us to hear about that from you,

00:41:27.760 --> 00:41:31.820
and in a very thoughtful
way that probably puts

00:41:31.820 --> 00:41:34.360
into words what we
experience in these concerts,

00:41:34.360 --> 00:41:36.630
because a lot of us are regulars

00:41:36.630 --> 00:41:39.600
and we share these moments
together we might never speak

00:41:39.600 --> 00:41:40.900
about what happened.

00:41:40.900 --> 00:41:43.320
We don't necessarily know
what the artist was intending,

00:41:43.320 --> 00:41:46.340
but I guarantee that in the
concerts that really touch us,

00:41:46.340 --> 00:41:49.900
whether it's you guys or another
ensemble, there are these moments

00:41:49.900 --> 00:41:53.100
that as you said are really
affecting people in ways

00:41:53.100 --> 00:41:56.250
that they didn't really
think could happen.

00:41:56.250 --> 00:41:58.790
Well, I guess one more question
then we have to let them go.

