00:42:14.900 --> 00:42:21.480
do you communicate among your very
small community about that aspect

00:42:21.480 --> 00:42:24.450
of the pieces you played together

00:42:24.450 --> 00:42:30.120
so that you were all
communicating the same message?

00:42:30.120 --> 00:42:31.420
&gt;&gt; Robin Scott: Absolutely.

00:42:31.420 --> 00:42:32.720
&gt;&gt; Peter Stumpf: I'm sorry.

00:42:32.720 --> 00:42:35.640
What is the question
specifically are we talking about?

00:42:35.640 --> 00:42:38.470
&gt;&gt; Do you communicate
among yourselves

00:42:38.470 --> 00:42:42.860
about the unspoken content
of the music you play,

00:42:42.860 --> 00:42:46.540
so that you are a more
homogeneous community?

00:42:46.540 --> 00:42:48.510
&gt;&gt; Peter Stumpf: No, we
don't speak about it.

00:42:48.510 --> 00:42:51.820
[ Laughs ]

00:42:51.820 --> 00:42:53.540
No, I mean actually we do.

00:42:53.540 --> 00:42:59.500
We do. But I think it's
actually the same thing happening

00:42:59.500 --> 00:43:01.690
in the group itself.

00:43:01.690 --> 00:43:06.930
A lot of what we're doing we
couldn't actually talk about.

00:43:06.930 --> 00:43:08.550
It's impossible.

00:43:08.550 --> 00:43:11.790
And that's where the
mystery comes in.

00:43:11.790 --> 00:43:13.090
How are we doing?

00:43:13.090 --> 00:43:15.890
Like how does that even happen?

00:43:15.890 --> 00:43:18.310
That's a real mystery, you know,

00:43:18.310 --> 00:43:22.290
and I think we experience this
kind of thing all the time.

00:43:22.290 --> 00:43:24.330
And sometimes we just don't
even think about the fact

00:43:24.330 --> 00:43:28.510
that we're experiencing it, but we
are, even just amongst ourselves.

00:43:28.510 --> 00:43:31.970
You know, because things change
from one orchestra to the next,

00:43:31.970 --> 00:43:35.900
even from one minute to
the next in a rehearsal.

00:43:35.900 --> 00:43:39.830
You couldn't always define
all of those elements

00:43:39.830 --> 00:43:42.810
that are shifting and changing.

00:43:42.810 --> 00:43:47.840
And it's just kind
of a real mystery.

00:43:47.840 --> 00:43:49.240
You know, how did that happen.

00:43:49.240 --> 00:43:53.940
I mean I had this experience
even very literally in a number

00:43:53.940 --> 00:44:00.400
of instances in my life
where something changed

00:44:00.400 --> 00:44:04.070
and there was an acknowledgement
that that had happened,

00:44:04.070 --> 00:44:08.280
but nobody can really
define or say what it was.

00:44:08.280 --> 00:44:16.260 position:56%
You know, except that it was more of
a connection between the musicians.

00:44:16.260 --> 00:44:23.120
&gt;&gt; Robin Scott: But also we do
absolutely talk about what sort

00:44:23.120 --> 00:44:26.520
of quality what we want
to convey, so that we --

00:44:26.520 --> 00:44:31.850
I think the effort of trying

00:44:31.850 --> 00:44:36.990 position:56%
to describe even these indescribable
things is very good to go

00:44:36.990 --> 00:44:40.890
through because it makes you really
think about how you want to sound

00:44:40.890 --> 00:44:44.860 position:56%
and what you want to convey and
then if you do that also as a group,

00:44:44.860 --> 00:44:50.410
then you can find that you have
a better more cohesive vision

00:44:50.410 --> 00:44:51.910
for the piece.

00:44:51.910 --> 00:44:56.990
So, yes, there's some things that
you can't always get 100 percent

00:44:56.990 --> 00:44:58.880
with words to describe music,

00:44:58.880 --> 00:45:02.280
but it's I think a good
exercise actually to go

00:45:02.280 --> 00:45:04.530
as far as you can oftentimes.

00:45:04.530 --> 00:45:05.830
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Great.

